# LitBridge Backend

Unified biomedical search platform. Accepts PICO/Boolean queries, federates across PubMed, Europe PMC, OpenAlex, and ClinicalTrials.gov in parallel. Deduplicates into Golden Records, enriches with AI summaries and citation metrics, resolves Open Access full-text. Enforces PRISMA systematic review methodology.

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|-----------|
| Framework | FastAPI (async-first) |
| Package Manager | uv + pyproject.toml + uv.lock |
| Agent Orchestration | LangGraph (stateful multi-agent graphs) |
| Database | PostgreSQL + SQLAlchemy 2.0 async + Alembic |
| Cache | Redis (24h page cache, OA memoization, rate limit counters) |
| AI/LLM | OpenRouter (GPT-4o-mini / Claude) for TLDR fallback |
| Semantic Data | Semantic Scholar API (TLDR, citations) |
| OA Resolution | OpenAlex OA fields, Unpaywall API, Europe PMC full-text |
| HTTP Client | httpx (async, shared clients per source) |
| Logging | structlog (JSON structured) |
| Testing | pytest + pytest-asyncio + httpx TestClient |
| Deployment | Docker multi-stage with uv, Gunicorn + Uvicorn |

## Multi-Agent Architecture (A through E)

```
User Query (PICO/Boolean)
    │
    ▼
Agent A ─── Syntax Translator (Adapters)
    │       Translates PubMed Boolean → source-specific dialects
    ▼
Agent B ─── Federated Fetcher (Orchestrator)
    │       Parallel async calls to all 4 APIs, rate-limited
    ▼
Agent C ─── PRISMA Deduplication Engine
    │       DOI/PMID hard match → fuzzy title soft match → Golden Records
    ▼
 ── FIRST PAINT (< 2s) ── return deduplicated results to client ──
    │
    ▼  (background, non-blocking)
Agent D ─── Semantic Enrichment
    │       Semantic Scholar TLDR + citations, LLM fallback
    ▼
Agent E ─── Open Access Resolver
            OA cascade: OpenAlex → Unpaywall → Europe PMC
```

## Architecture Layers (Strict)

```
src/
├── api/v1/          # Routers — thin, validate with Pydantic, HTTP concerns only
├── services/        # Business logic — orchestration, agent coordination
├── repositories/    # Data access — one per external API + one for DB
├── models/          # SQLAlchemy/SQLModel ORM models
├── schemas/         # Pydantic: UnifiedRecord, SearchRequest, PrismaCounts, etc.
├── ai/              # LangGraph graphs, nodes, LLM client
│   ├── graphs/      # Workflow graph definitions
│   └── nodes/       # Individual node functions (fetch, dedup, enrich, resolve_oa)
├── core/            # Config, security, deps, exceptions, middleware
└── main.py          # FastAPI app + lifespan (Redis pool, DB engine, httpx clients)
```

## Naming Conventions

- `snake_case` for variables, functions, modules, directories
- `CamelCase` for Pydantic models, SQLModel classes, exceptions
- Services: `{Domain}Service` — Repositories: `{Source}Repository`
- Schemas: `{Entity}Create`, `{Entity}Response`, `{Entity}Update`
- Adapters: `{Source}Adapter` — Nodes: `{verb}_{noun}` (e.g., `fetch_sources`)

## Hard Rules

1. No DB/HTTP calls in routers — delegate to services/repositories
2. No business logic in repositories — only data access
3. Async for all I/O — `httpx.AsyncClient`, `AsyncSession`, `redis.asyncio`
4. Type hints everywhere — all signatures, all return types
5. Pydantic for all API boundaries — never accept/return raw dicts
6. structlog for logging — no `print()`, no stdlib logging
7. Custom exceptions mapped to HTTPException only in routers
8. First paint < 2 seconds — dedup is fast path, enrichment is background
9. Partial failure is OK — if one source fails, return results from others
10. Cache aggressively — Redis for API responses, OA status, enrichment
